	<h1> Watershed Advocacy </h1>

	<p>
		The diverse membership of the Coalition for the Delaware River Watershed is involved in all areas of Watershed protection and restoration—from helping to educate the next generation of caretakers, to working with decisionmakers on effective legislative and policy strategies, to preserving the wealth of flora and fauna that call the Watershed home.  Each of our members is a vital advocate for the health and wellbeing of the Delaware River, its many tributaries, and the millions of acres of surrounding forests, wetlands and scenic wild places.

		The Coalition benefits from the individual strengths and talents of our members—a rich blend of local, regional, state, and national groups.  In return, membership in the Coalition enhances the ability of our members to make a difference by leveraging their collective voices and know-how for greater impact.  By joining forces around shared concerns, we hope to better safeguard the Delaware River Watershed and its remarkable resources for future generations to enjoy.  Some of the ways the Coalition will advocate on behalf of these concerns is through circulation of sign-on letters, coordinating outreach to legislators and agencies throughout the Watershed, and publicizing the work of its members.  
	</p>

	<h2> Top Priorities </h2>

	<p>The Coalition is currently focused on two significant initiatives expected to bring lasting protection to the Watershed, restore degraded resources, and help enrich and strengthen partnerships among the groups working within its boundaries. </p>

	
	<h2>Delaware River Basin Conservation Act (DRBCA)</h2>
	<p> 
		Anticipated to be re-introduced in early 2013, the DRBCA creates a non-regulatory Delaware River Basin Restoration Program within the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to adopt and implement a watershed-wide investment strategy, in consultation with federal and state agencies and other partners. The DRBCA also provides for a competitive grant program and technical assistance to support locally driven, on-the-ground projects.  By providing for a coordinated conservation strategy and dedicated federal support, the DRBCA would finally allow the Delaware River Watershed to benefit from the same level of attention focused on other major basins of the United States.   The Coalition is a proud co-sponsor of an upcoming Congressional briefing to accompany re-introduction of the DRBCA and will continue undertake additional activities to support passage of this vitally important legislation.  To learn more about the DRBCA, click here (hyperlink to actual legislation – not yet available)
